    "result": {"data":{"challengeNode":{"challenge":{"videoId":null,"videoLocaleIds":null,"bilibiliIds":null,"title":"Task 37","description":"<section id=\"description\">\n<p>For most verbs, if you want to make a negative sentence in the past tense, simply put <code>didn't</code> in front of the main verb.\n<code>Didn't</code> is short for <code>did not</code>.</p>\n<p>Remember that the main verb stays in its simple form. Only the auxiliary verb <code>did</code> is conjugated. For example:</p>\n<p><strong>Affirmative sentence in the past</strong>: <code>I worked yesterday</code> - The Verb <code>work</code> is conjugated to the past.</p>\n<p><strong>Negative sentence in the past</strong>: <code>I didn't work yesterday</code> - Only the auxiliary verb is conjugated to the past.</p>\n</section>","challengeType":19,"helpCategory":"English","superBlock":"a2-english-for-developers","block":"learn-how-to-ask-and-share-about-educational-and-professional-background","fields":{"slug":"/learn/a2-english-for-developers/learn-how-to-ask-and-share-about-educational-and-professional-background/task-37","blockName":"learn-how-to-ask-and-share-about-educational-and-professional-background","tests":[]},"question":{"text":"<p>If someone says that <code>Sophie didn't study computer science</code>, what could you understand from this sentence?</p>","answers":[{"answer":"<p>Sophie enjoyed the computer science degree</p>","feedback":"<p>Using <code>didn't</code> suggests she did not study it, contradicting the idea of enjoying it.</p>"},{"answer":"<p>Computer science is not something Sophie studied in college</p>","feedback":null},{"answer":"<p>Sophie always studies computer science</p>","feedback":"<p>This expression refers to a regular habit, not a specific event in the past.</p>"},{"answer":"<p>Sophie is looking forward to studying computer science</p>","feedback":"<p>This option is about future anticipation.</p>"}],"solution":2},"scene":{"setup":{"background":"company2-center.png","c